BRFSS Data Set

The differences between BRFSS and NHANES. First, while the CDC organizes the BRFSS and provides supports to states doing the BRFSS, the data collection is actually run at the state level. Next, instead of running around neighborhoods in a MEC, the BRFSS does anonymous phone surveys by simply randomly generating phone numbers, calling them, and doing the survey. Admittedly, BRFSS was a little late to the gate in getting cell phone numbers into the sampling frame, but they worked very hard on it. And now their sampling appears to be fairly robust. Also, they compile the dataset annually instead of every two years like NHANES. Next, there is this concept in the BRFSS of core questions and questions from modules. Because the feds organize the BRFSS, there are certain questions they insist are asked pretty much the same way every year as these are part of the core questions every year that states are obligated to ask. This way, the feds can trend rates of, say, smoking. But states are the ones who are actually doing the survey. Therefore, they have their own needs. And to accommodate those, they use different sets of validated BRFSS modules each year so they can keep tabs on their state-specific problems. For example, some states have cities with smog problems, and those states may choose to include the asthma / adult asthma history module one year. Or states experiencing a spike in racially-motivated violence might choose to include the reactions to race module that year. The answers to the core questions are available publicly in a huge dataset you can download. Some researchers dont trust the BRFSS because people are expected to self-report conditions such as having diabetes. Unlike in NHANES, there is a lack of clinical confirmation of self-reported conditions in other metrics in BRFSS. But many analyses have shown that the BRFSS is pretty accurate. Some, such as myself, believe that the reduced selection bias in a large sample associated with BRFSS helps overcome the possible misclassification problems introduced by the phone versus in-person survey and that these biases are preferable to the more severe selection bias present in the smaller NHANES sample. But there is no right answer, whatever floats your boat. So some see the main drawback to the BRFSS is a lack of clinical confirmation due to the nature of it being a phone survey. There is another drawback. Unfortunately, only the results of the core questions are available publicly with documentation. If you want state module questions, youll have to contact that states public health department and see if theyre willing to share their module data with you. So now, Im done with our quick review of US risk factors surveillance systems: the NHANES and the BRFSS.

Research Questions

Relevance : Perceived Insufficient Rest or Sleep among Veterans:Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System 2009
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3659378/pdf/jcsm.9.6.577.pdf

Research Questions : The purpose of this study is to investigate whether self-reported insufficient rest or sleep varies in relation to Veteran status and to identify high-risk groups of Veterans

Subpopulation : Stratified Veterans from Survey data with two stratas - newly transitioned veterans and long-term veterans

Exposure : Independent variables : Something you think causes, former is associated with disease or outcome * Independent Categorical Variable : Alcohol Consumption

Outcome : Dependent variables : Something you think is affected by exposure * Dependent Continuous Variable : Sleep Per Night

  • Independent Categorical Variable : Alcohol Consumption
  • Dependent Categorical Binary Variable : Asthma

So our goal is to identify confounding variables between exposure, alcohol drinking, and our outcomes, which are sleep duration and asthma, which are not on the causal pathway between the exposure and the outcome.

Understanding Confounders and Web of Causation

Independent (exposure) variable : Alcohol Consumption Dependent (outcome) variable : Insufficient Sleep Candidate Confounders : Age, Sex, Race/Ethinicity, Marital Status, Highest Education Level, Physical Activity Status, Highest Education Level, Self-Reported Generated Health, Obesity, Smoking Status, Having Health Insurance Candidate Confounder not available in BRFSS : Sleep Apnea

Required Data Processing Function

  The following function is used in the exploratory data analysis to reduce the brfss2013 data to just those observations that had a value for each of the variables under consideration - allprep:
  
allprep <- function(...) {
    study <- analytic %>%
        dplyr::select(...) 
    
    return(study[complete.cases(study),])
}
ASTHMA4_f <- factor(analytic$ASTHMA4, labels = c("No Asthma", "Yes Asthma"))
analytic$ASTHMA4_f <- factor(analytic$ASTHMA4, labels = c("No Asthma", "Yes Asthma"))

Research Question 1:

JCSM (URL linked above) concludes that veterans sleep time is insufficient and needs to be targeted to improve, this research is to identify all the variables associated with sleep time and indentifying if they are corelated keeping in mind that corelation does not imply causation. Is there any association with ASTHMA and Alcohol consumption, alcohol consumption and sleep time. Since ASTHMA is a confounding outcome variable, here we are trying to associate Alcohol consumption to Asthma.

Research Question 2:

Are Veterans smoking habits and their age group associated with the number of days they reported where their physical health was not good?

Exploratory Data Analysis for Question 2

To determine if there is an association between smoking habits and the number of days where physical health was not good, the summary statistics for measures of center and measures of the spread were determined. The skew of the data was also determined by comparing the mean and median - SMKR_AGE_HLTH_SUM:

SMKR_AGE_HLTH <- allprep(X_SMOKER3_f,X_AGE_G_f, PHYSHLTH) 

SMKR_AGE_HLTH_SUM <- SMKR_AGE_HLTH %>% 
    group_by(X_AGE_G_f, X_SMOKER3_f) %>%
    filter(X_SMOKER3_f != "Unknown") %>%
    summarize(Q1 = quantile(PHYSHLTH, 0.25), MEAN = mean(PHYSHLTH), MEDIAN = median(PHYSHLTH),Q3 = quantile(PHYSHLTH, 0.75), IQR = IQR(PHYSHLTH), STDEV = sd(PHYSHLTH)) %>%
    mutate(SKEW = ifelse(MEAN > MEDIAN, "RIGHT", "LEFT")) %>%
    arrange(desc(MEAN))

##Summary These summary statistics indicate that 100% of the respondents of almost all of the smoking habit and age group combinations report more than zero days with physical health that was not good. The distribution for each category is heavily right-skewed, especially given that the possible maximum value for physhlth is 30. The mean and Q3 give a sense as to some differences between each category. The mean number of days with poor physical health for the two current smoking categories are generally higher than the mean days of poor physical health of the former smokers and the never smoked category. Moreover, the mean number of days with poor physical health for each age group increases as age increases.

  These measures suggest some association between whether a person smokes and how many days of poor physical health they have during the month. Current smokers tend to have higher number of poor physical health days. In addition, the measures indicate some association between a respondents age and how many days of poor physical health they may have during month. Older age groups tend to have a higher number of poor physical health days.

Summary

Excluding the respondents who had zero days of poor physical health, a similar association pattern appears as before, but, now, unique median values are present. The two categories of current smokers have higher mean and median values than for former smokers and those who never smoked. The large IQR values for many of the categories indicate there is a great spread of values considering both this version of the data and the data that includes zero values. This large spread of values means there is a lot of overlap between the densities of each category, which limits the strength of any association drawn from the data.

  Both the associations and the large spread and overlap in the data can be visualized with multiple boxplots:    
no0_dat3 <- analytic %>% filter(PHYSHLTH !=30 )
ggplot(no0_dat3, aes(x = X_AGE_G_f, y = PHYSHLTH, fill = X_SMOKER3_f)) + 
    geom_boxplot() +
    scale_fill_manual(values = heat_hcl(6, h = c(20,-80), l = c(75,40), c =c(40,80), power = 1)) +

    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

##Summary

  These boxplots display a version of the same information as the table above, except the mean and sd values are not plotted. The boxplots give a sense of the large IQR or spread in the data, especially for the older age groups indicating that the distribution of days with poor physical health ranges over almost all the possible options from 1-30 in these cases. The IQR also shows how some of these categories have large overlaps in their distribution, which reduces the strength of any association in the data as this means some of the distributions are not significantly distinct. In addition, the medians generally show the decreasing number of poor physical health days both as one is younger and does not smoke.
